```json
{
  "application": "SLURM",
  "details": {
    "job_name": "biLouvainMethod",
    "mail_user": "p.pesantezcabrera@wsu.edu",
    "queue": "debug",
    "nodes": 1,
    "time": "00:10:00",
    "memory": "10GB",
    "partition": "project",
    "mail_type": "ALL",
    "modules": "gcc/6.1.0",
    "executable": "biLouvain",
    "num_processes": 1,
    "num_threads": 1,
    "order": 3,
    "cutoff_phases": 0.0,
    "cutoff_iterations": 0.01,
    "datasets": [
      "biSBM301",
      "biSBM30"
    ],
    "folder": "/global/homes/p/ppesante/biLouvain/inputData/"
  }
}
```

This script uses SLURM to run a job on a cluster. The job is named "biLouvainMethod" and is submitted to the "debug" queue. It requests one node, runs for a maximum of 10 minutes, and requires 10GB of memory. The job is run on the "project" partition. The script also uses the "gcc/6.1.0" module and executes a binary called "biLouvain".  The script processes data from multiple files in a folder. It uses several parameters like order, cutoff phases and iterations. It iterates through a list of datasets.
